Without revealing too many details for those who have not yet had the opportunity to see the show, he discusses the topic of M nchhausen's replacement syndrome – a mental illness found in caregivers who act as if the healthy person they are dealing with was afflicted with a physical or mental illness.
There are different types of this condition, e.g., in the form of the Munchhausen syndrome, which consists in causing symptoms of a particular disease in one's body.
A replacement for Munchhausen's syndrome is to simulate that the person in our care has certain ailments.
It is also called an invented and induced disease, and it is treated as violence against a child.
This is a rare condition that usually involves a parent exaggerating symptoms or causing symptoms so that it looks like his or her child is sick.
What are the symptoms of the replacement Munchhausen syndrome?
Symptoms of this disease may vary, however, the NHS notes the following example behaviors:
Convincing medical staff that a healthy-looking child feels bad, however.
Exaggerating or inventing symptoms.
Falsifying the results to make a child feel sick, such as giving glucose to urine samples to make it look like the child has diabetes.
Inducing symptoms of the disease, e.g. giving children unnecessary medications and other substances.
How often is the replacement syndrome of Munchhausen present?
It is difficult to estimate how often this disorder occurs, as many cases of the disease are not reported.
A study published in 2000 indicates that there have been 89 cases of this disorder per 100,000 people in more than two years.
What should be done if there are suspicions that the child may be in danger?
Contact your local special services department or call the NSPCC Child Protection Helpline by dialing 0808 800 5000.
