Brother Sentenced to Life Sentence for Killing Honorary Social Media Stars Qandeel Baloch
Qandeel Baloch, who became a star thanks to photos posted on social media, was strangled in July 2016.
Pakistani social media star Qandeel Baloch's brother was found guilty on Friday of her murder and sentenced to life imprisonment for the most notorious "honour killing" in this patriarchal country.
Baloch, who gained fame by posting bold selfies – polite by Western standards, but in heavily misogynistic Pakistan considered provocative – was strangled in July 2016.
Her brother Muhammad Waseem was arrested.
A few days later, he said during a press conference that he had no remorse for his actions and stated that he had "obviously" murdered his sister and that her behavior was "unacceptable".
His lawyer Sardar Mehmood told AFP that a court in the western city of Multan found his client guilty and sentenced him to life in the long-awaited sentence.
"Inshallah (if God permits) will be acquitted by a higher court," he said.
Baloch's mother, Anwar Mai, had previously told AFP that she hoped her son would be acquitted.
"He is innocent.
She was my daughter, and this is my son," she said.
The Baloch murder has hit the forefront of global news services and has resumed calls for action against the epidemic of so-called honor killings, in which victims – usually women – are killed for violating patriarchal social principles.
Women were set on fire, strangled, shot or daggered for such offenses as choosing their own husband or, as in the case of Baloch, for bringing "shame" to their family by manifesting their own sexuality.
The killings are usually carried out by a close relative.
Under Pakistani law, Qisas (blood money) and Diyat (retaliation) can ask their closest victims for forgiveness.
Three months after Baloch's murder, parliament passed new legislation introducing a life sentence for honor killings.
However, whether or not a murder is considered an honourable offence remains the responsibility of the judge, which means that murderers can theoretically invoke another motive and be acquitted.
In the case of Baloch, her parents initially insisted that their son should not be shown grace under any circumstances.
However, devastated by the thought that they might lose him too, they changed their minds and declared that they wanted his acquittal.
The international outrage caused by the murder prompted the Pakistani state to take an unprecedented step and declare itself an heir with his parents, thus forcing the case to move forward.
One of Baloch's more famous achievements is offering to strip in front of the Pakistani cricket team and wearing a decoiled purple dress on Valentine's Day.
She was criticized and threatened, but many people, including young people, saw her as breaking the boundaries in a country where posing as a Kim Kardashian-style figure could be considered a bold and political move to empower women.
