The CSIRO agency estimates that about 1560 kg of plastic enters our waterways every hour, and that the greater part of it flows into the bay through storm sewerage.
"After such powerful rainfall, the bay ... looks quite tragic," said Dr. Dafforn.
Two-thirds of the pollution comes from rainwater.
However, as with the iceberg, the Sydney Bay problem is much more serious below the surface of the water, as 70% of the plastic entering the ocean goes to the bottom of the sea.
"In my opinion, unless you spend time underwater, you can't really realize what's in there deep down," said Richard Nicholls, owner of Dive Centre Manly, noting that he and his team are pulling about 500 kg of plastic out of the water on their own each year.
