It's overwhelming... more than half of what we find at the bottom are plastic meshes.
The other 50% are things that are at least made of plastic.
When you look at the bay, it looks beautiful, and people can't believe that all this plastic and all that other garbage is being brought out right from under the surface.
Jeremy Brown, co-founder and managing director of Ocean Protect, stated that there are ways that people – both locals and tourists – could help reduce the amount of plastic and debris entering our waterways.
"It has to start at the source," he said.
We need to reduce the amount of plastic we use, better conduct material recovery, and be more aware of what we are draining in the sewage that eventually goes into the oceans.
If we destroy the ocean, we are doomed because 50% of the oxygen we breathe comes from the ocean.
