The study established a way to mask some cancer cells in both humans and marsupials, using a group of proteins called PRC2, which disables a marker that would otherwise signal the immune system to attack the cancer.
This may pose the greatest challenge in the treatment of small cell lung cancer, neuroblastoma, and a type of skin cancer called Merkel cell cancer.
"The huge significance of this project is that in patients who sometimes develop resistance to immune therapies, we may be able to reverse this process," said AAP chief researcher Mark Dawson of Peter Mac.
Existing therapies can be directed to re-inclusion of markers, proteins called MHC, which will allow the immune system to recognize cancer cells.
"This potentially has far-reaching implications for people with lung cancer," said Professor Dawson.
"This is one of the most common diseases on earth.
And maybe we can treat her a lot better.
The researchers also hope that the discovery will one day be used to treat the face tumors of the Tasmanian devil, where cancer cells similarly avoid detection.
"It is remarkable that exactly the same process occurs (in the case of cancers in humans and in Tasmanian devils)," said Professor Dawson.
