Accident victims will receive pensions
On Friday, a regulation is coming into force to ensure that those seriously affected by accidents continue to pay their pensions, the Financial Ombudsman reports.
It is about the Act of 9 July 2019 on the special rights of persons injured in the event of exhaustion of the guarantee sum determined on the basis of the provisions in force before 1 January 2006.
It concerns people who were injured before 1 January 2006.
At the time, there were much lower guarantee sums than today, hence in some cases insurers have already stopped paying annuities.
"I am happy with this regulation, because our institution has been striving for many years to create a mechanism that will allow to provide those seriously injured in accidents with a guarantee of financial support from motor insurance or farmer's OC despite the exhaustion of the guarantee sum," says Aleksander Daszewski, legal counsel at the office of the Financial Ombudsman.
According to the Financial Ombudsman, this was necessary, because these are often very tragic situations involving people in very poor health who, due to an accident, cannot work, and at the same time bear significant costs of post-accident rehabilitation treatment.
Some of them no longer received compensatory pensions and for increased needs due to the need for further treatment or rehabilitation due to the exhaustion of the so-called guarantee sums on OC policies.
Parts of it threatened in the coming years.
By January 1, 2006, the insurer's liability limits were significantly lower than the current one.
Therefore, the problem of exhaustion of the guarantee sum in previous years most often affected people who suffered damage in the 1990s.
Back then, the guarantee totals were very low, and the economic conditions caused prices to rise.
"We also noticed that this problem was also affected by a number of mostly young people who suffered damage during the period when the amount of the sum was EUR 350,000 for each injured person in the accident.
It currently stands at 5.21 million euros per event, regardless of the number of victims.
So this is a huge difference from earlier periods, hence the problem required the intervention of the legislator", recalls Aleksander Daszewski.
He explains that since the guarantee sum is increased from time to time, the legislator accepted that the upper limit of the liability of the Insurance Guarantee Fund would be the guarantee sum in force at the time of the claim for the payment of an annuity to the Fund.
This rule applies if the insurance company is not obliged to pay an annuity on the basis of a court decision fixing a different amount of the guarantee sum than that fixed in the civil liability insurance contract.
This is the case when the sum of the guarantee is increased by court pursuant to Article 3571 of the Civil Code, which allows modification of the existing liability relationship.
"In recent days, we have sent letters to people who in the past have asked us to intervene.
In them we inform about the new powers and of course we provide the possibility of providing further support in the event of any problems", says Aleksander Daszewski.
