Potential research on renewable biofuels may help reduce emissions
While electric cars and Semi Tesla have dominated news sites in recent years, one issue seems to elude renewable energy – aircraft.
However, a professor at the University of Alberta has developed a technology that will allow renewable biofuels to be used as aviation fuel.
Dr. David Bressler is a professor at the University of Alberta in the Department of Agriculture, Life Sciences and the Environment who began working on this project in 2003.
His laboratory develops hydrocarbon fuel obtained from fatty wastes such as restaurant fat, animal fats and rapeseed oil.
Unlike ethanol and other biofuels, this technology can use lower-quality oils during production, resulting in an estimated 85% lower carbon emissions than oil fuels, as well as using waste from other industries in the process.
This technology is designed to mimic hydrocarbons present in petroleum fuels.
"What our technology did in the first generation," Bressler said, "is [produce] hydrocarbons that are identical molecules to diesel."
While this opens up a new possibility of using biofuel, previously developed biofuel products tended to destabilize at lower temperatures, which was a serious threat for high-altitude aircraft.
"The aviation fuel problem is a bit of a vicious circle," Bressler said.
