Rule of law instead of rule of law.
"Despite not having enough votes to amend the Constitution, the ruling majority has made a number of changes to the state system, posing threats to the protection of the rule of law and the principle of tri-division of power," the Helsinki Foundation for Human Rights wrote in a report published Thursday.
The report "Government of the law instead of the rule of law" documents, among other things, changes in the justice system and in the sphere of protection of fundamental rights and freedoms.
The Helsinki Foundation for Human Rights (HFPC) released a report on Thursday entitled "Government of the law instead of the rule of law.
Threats to the protection of human rights in Poland in 2015-2019".
The Foundation assesses in its report that between 2015 and 2019, the largest regression in the field of human rights protection in Poland after 1989 was recorded.
"Despite not having enough votes to amend the Constitution, the ruling majority has made a number of changes to the state system, posing threats to the protection of the rule of law and the principle of tri-division of power.
By aligning the law with political goals, the rule of law has been replaced by the rule of law," write HFPC experts.
What about the HFPC report?
The report documents changes in the functioning of the judiciary, independent institutions (such as the public media or the Ombudsman) and in the area of protection of fundamental rights and freedoms (including freedom of assembly, women's rights, LGBT rights and the right to a fair trial).
The report also summarizes the ongoing dispute between the Polish authorities and the European Union for three years.
"Over the past four years, for the first time and on such a scale, we have observed the use of the right to pursue particular party interests.
This translated into the ongoing crisis of the rule of law, as well as weakening the entire human rights protection system in Poland," emphasized attorney Marcin Wolny, one of the authors of the report.
Protection of human rights
As indicated in the report, the last four years have been "a period of systemic change in both the state and human rights protection."
Over the past four years, the Sejm has adopted more than 20 pieces of legislation crucial from the point of view of human rights protection.
"Changes were often accepted at a hasty pace, without public consultation and despite objections from the legal community, the Ombudsman or international organizations," explained lawyer Małgorzata Szuleka, co-author of the report.
According to the report, the main trends observed in the past four years are: "weakening of independent institutions (including courts and prosecutors), failure to respect binding court judgments and recommendations of international institutions, and weakening of guarantees of human rights protection".
The state authorities did not respond
The Helsinki Foundation for Human Affairs considered "those situations in which the state authorities did not react or directly disregard the emerging cases of aggression".
Foundation experts noted that some changes were made in the atmosphere of attacks on individual institutions or professional groups or groups exposed to discrimination.
The Foundation points out that the result of the state's activity in the field of limiting the rule of law is an ongoing dispute between the Polish authorities and the European Union, as well as a number of recommendations from entities of international law.
"The failure to implement these recommendations not only weakens Poland's position as a leader of democratic change in the region of Central and Eastern Europe, but also exposes the Polish state to liability for violating European Union law or the European Convention on Human Rights," the report said.
