Doodle celebrates Google's 21st birthday
It would be hard to imagine a world without Google today.
In the search engine, we look for answers to all the questions that torment us.
What are we looking for on Google?
"What is it?", "Where?", "How?" and "How much?" are some of the favorite categories searched by Poles.
According to the data of the giant, last year we were happy to ask, among others, about "Where is the storm?", "How to make asparagus?" and "How many fingers does a horse have?", "How to get rid of fruit flies?", "How to eat kaki?".
Today, the search engine celebrates its twenty-first birthday.
Its users – and in Poland as many as 96% of people use "uncle Google" – are welcomed today by a special Google Doodle.
This time it's not animated.
Google recalls its birthday by showing a desktop computer with a monitor, mouse and keyboard, and in the lower right corner a digital date was printed – as in a 1990s photo.
Cataloging information
The search engine was created for a specific purpose – it was supposed to catalog all possible information and make it available via the Internet.
Its name is a pun.
It comes from the mathematical term googol meaning the number ten raised to the power of the hundredth.
The name was also intended to reflect the company's intention to index as many pages from the world's Internet resources as possible.
Google Search was founded by Sergey Brin and Larry Page in 1996 as part of their student project at Stanford University.
It was based on a mathematical analysis of the relationship between the parties, which worked better than the usual methods of sorting results based on the frequency of occurrence of a given phrase.
In the beginning, the search engine was called BlackRub, referring to the English word blacklink, which denotes the number of pages linking to a given result.
Page and Brin founded a company operating under Google Inc. on September 7, 1998, and soon thereafter launched the now famous google.com website.
What's next, Google?
In December 1998, PC Magazine reported the extremely high relevance of Google search results.
Then the history of the company looks almost like a fairy tale - rapid development with each month, conquering more markets and increasing the value of the company.
As early as June 2000, Google's URL index has more than a billion entries, making Page and Brin's work the largest search engine in the world.
Currently, the company founded by Page and Brin is one of the leading players in the IT market.
So is there any further room for development?
"The mission of Google is to organize the world's information resources to be widely available and useful, even though we have made great progress in this area, we still have a very long way to go to achieve this goal," Piotr Zalewski of Google Poland assured in an interview with "Newsweek".
