A new study suggests that working with exposure to high concentrations of plant protection products can translate into a high risk of heart disease later in life.
This was the case with a group of Japanese-Americans in Hawaii who had been studied for over 30 years.
The researchers found that compared to men who did not work with plant protection products, those who had the most contact with them were 45% more likely to have heart disease or stroke.
"This study highlights the need to use personal protective equipment for the duration of exposure to pesticides at work and the importance of record keeping in medical records of exposure to such agents at work, as well as controlling standard factors that increase the incidence of heart disease," said study co-author Dr. Beatriz Rodriguez.
She is a professor of geriatric medicine at the University of Hawaii in the Manoa district.
The results were based on data from more than 6,000 men on the island of Oahu who participated in the Kuakini Honolulu cardiology program.
As the researchers pointed out, the results of the study may not apply to women and other populations, as it was only for men of Japanese origin.
Pesticides have a long half-life, so the effects of their effects on health can be felt many years after contact with these substances.
In this case, the most visible results were observed within 10 years after contact with plant protection substances.
In a press release, Rodriguez said: "After 34 years of male observation, the relationship between pesticide exposure and heart disease and stroke was no longer significant."
This was probably because aging factors became more important, which masked the possible cause and effect relationship between exposure to pesticides and cardiovascular disease incidence in later years of life.
The researchers did not find a significant relationship between exposure to small to moderate amounts of plant protection products and an increased risk of heart disease or stroke.
