Exhibition of Elizabeth I's lost dress at Hampton Court Palace
Interspersed with silver thread, the gown made of the finest silk chamlot was elaborately decorated with embroidery depicting vegetation, animals and butterflies.
For Eleri Lynn, curator of the Historic Royal Palaces Foundation exhibition, this meant only one thing.
The faded cloth hanging for 100 years on the wall of the tiny rural parish church she was looking at could only have been a lost part of Elizabeth I's dressing room.
Three years after Lynn stumbled across a sumptuous altar cloth in Bacton, Herefordshire, Elizabeth's missing gown is due next month for an exhibition at Hampton Court Palace, close to the same rooms where the Tudor queen could wear it more than 450 years ago.
The measure of the significance of this discovery is that of the entire collection of royal gowns, only one more element of the 16th-century gown survives.
While there is no conclusive evidence that Elizabeth would ever wear this dress, three years of research has strengthened experts in the belief that she must have been part of the royal wardrobe.
The "swords", an incredibly expensive fabric, was legally reserved only for the most important members of the royal court, and the virtuoso quality of embroidered plants and flowers, later enriched with deer, dogs, butterflies, fishermen and bear, indicates that the dress belonged to the most prominent of the people.
The dress, at the time it was sewn, may have cost the equivalent of the Tudor estate.
"Moreover, in the 1990s, at the end of Elizabeth's reign, she felt threatened by other women at court and would not tolerate rivals wearing such fine fabrics," Lynn claims.
"As this is a very important statement, I've asked a lot of people from the environment to look at the dress.
I really enjoyed seeing the dress, too, and they were practically convinced that we had an element of royal wardrobe in front of us.
The long, re-life of the dress, trimmed to serve as an altar cloth in the dark church of St Faith in Bacton, is not as unexpected as it might seem.
Bacton is the settlement from which Blanche Parry came, Elizabeth's closest lady of the court, who served the queen her entire long life and with whom the cloth in question was identified in local legends.
Although the dress was created after her death in 1590, experts believe that Elizabeth had to give it to the Parry family or parish in memory of Blanche before her death in 1603.
After more than a thousand hours of restoration work, four hundred of which passed on the most delicate hand sewing using specially dyed silk and thin surgical needles, the altar cloth will go to the exhibition next to the Hatfield House palace's temporary rental portrait of "Rainbow Portrait", one of the most famous paintings of the time depicting Elizabeth dressed in a similar gown.
"When working with historical fabrics, the craftsmanship of the people who made them is really beginning to be respected," says Libby Thompson, head of conservation work, most of which took place in a converted greenhouse at Hampton Court Palace – the only large enough place to accommodate some of the priceless palace tapestries.
"Looking at the embroidery from the front and back, I started to feel great respect for those who made it.
I've never worked on anything so elitist.
An exhibition entitled "The Lost Dress of Elizabeth" will begin at Hampton Court Palace on October 12.
