Polish Rating
The autumn round of reviews of Poland's rating on 11 October will be completed by S&P and Moody's.
According to Fitch agency, Poland's rating remains the same as that issued at the end of March 2019.
At that time, the agency confirmed Poland's rating at the "A-" level with a stable outlook.
Of the three largest credit rating agencies, Poland's creditworthiness is highest rated by Moody's – at the "A2" level.
The rating of Poland according to Fitch and S&P is "A-", one level lower than Moody's.
The outlook for all assessments is stable.
What is a rating?
Rating agencies are created to help investors assess the risk scale of their investment activities.
The rating is given to companies, banks and states.
In the case of the latter, each assessment translates into economic attractiveness.
A rating is nothing more than a credit rating.
On its basis, decisions are made about who and for how much money to borrow.
Sometimes such information also suggests who is best not to grant any loans at all, because there is a considerable risk that the money will not be recovered.
A lower rating carries a higher risk.
In turn, the higher risk is high interest on the loan.
Each assessment must be reasoned and reasoned.
Ratings can be manipulated, but in this case, agencies risk losing their reputation.
At the moment, more than 90 percent of the global rating services market is controlled by three agencies: Standard & Poor's, Fitch and Moody's.
Each uses its own rating system.
