Ronald Lee Haskell: Man convicted of murdering his ex-wife's family in Texas
Ronald Lee Haskell, 39, was convicted of the 2014 murder of Stephen and Katie Stay and four of their five children in Spring, Texas.
According to authorities, he entered the Stays' home on July 9, 2014, demanding that his wife, Melannie Haskell, be revealed where he was separated from.
She wasn't there, but there was her sister, Katie Stay, and her family.
Stephen Stay, 39, Katie Stay, 33, two boys aged 13 and 4, and two girls aged 9 and 7, were killed when Haskell opened fire, according to the Harris County Sheriff's Office.
Only one family member survived, then 15-year-old Cassidy Stay.
Authorities said she was badly injured, but she managed to recover completely.
On Thursday, members of the jury rejected Ronald Lee Haskell's defense on the grounds of insanity.
The jury will reconvene on Monday to deliver a verdict.
The quantum internet is getting closer to reality – ScienceDaily
U.S. Army research results take the quantum internet one step closer.
Such an internet could offer military capabilities in terms of security, detection and timekeeping accuracy unavailable with the traditional networking approach.
The Center for Distributed Quantum Information Processing of the Military Research Laboratory for the Development of Combat Capabilities of the U.S. Army looked at researchers from the University of Insbruck who managed to achieve a record-breaking transfer of tangled state between matter and light – over a distance of 50 kilometers using fiber optic cables.
Confusion is the correlation that can arise between quanta such as qubits.
When two qubits are entangled and one qubit is measured, it will affect the measurement made on the other qubit, even if the other qubit is physically away.
"These [50 kilometres] are two orders of magnitude farther than was previously possible and it is a feasible distance to start building intercity quantum networks," said Dr. Ben Lanyon, an experimental physicist at the University of Innsbruck and lead researcher in the project, whose findings were published in the journal Nature, section Quantum Information.
Intercity quantum networks would consist of distant nodes of physical qubit networks that are entangled with each other despite the large physical distance.
The researchers found that this scattering of the entangled state is essential for the creation of the quantum internet.
"This demonstration is a big step forward in order to achieve a distributed state tangled on a large scale," said Dr. Sara Gamble, co-managing a military program to support this research.
The quality of the tangled state at the other end after the fiber optics have passed is also high enough to meet some of the requirements of some of the most difficult applications of quantum networks.
The research team began the experiment with a calcium atom trapped in an ion trap.
Using laser beams, the researchers typed a quantum state into the ion, while arousing it to emit a photon in which quantum information was stored.
As a result, the quantum states of the atom and the particles of light were entangled.
The challenge is to send the photon through a fiber optic cable.
"The photon emitted by the calcium ion has a wavelength of 854 nanometers and is quickly absorbed by the fiber optics," Lanyon said.
Therefore, his team initially sent a particle of light through a nonlinear crystal illuminated by a strong laser beam.
The wavelength of the photon has been converted to a value optimal from the point of view of long-distance transmission – the current standard telecommunication wavelength is 1550 nanometers.
The researchers then sent this photon through a 50-kilometer fiber optic cable.
Their measurements show that the atom and particles of light were still entangled even after the wavelength was transformed and the distance traveled.
"The decision to choose calcium means that this result sets a direct path for the formation of a tangled network of atomic clocks over long physical distances, because calcium can be co-trapped with a high-quality qubit 'clock'.
The Army is very much interested in tangled large-scale clock networks due to applications for precise positional determination, precise navigation and time synchronization," said Dr. Fredrik Fatemi, a military researcher who also co-manages the program.
